{
  "text": "Recent studies have shown that the use of Fe(III) complexes such as ferrioxalate with hydrogen peroxide in photo-irradiation is a new and promising attempt to degrade organic pollutants because ferrioxalate complexes have a very high molar absorption coefficient for wavelengths above 200 nm [CITATION_1] . However, the use of Fe(II) instead of Fe(III) has seldom been discussed. The complexes formed between Fe 2+ and oxalate are mainly the mono-, or bis-oxalate complexes (Fe II C 2 O 4 or Fe II (C 2 O 4 ) 2 2-), where the distribution of dominant species depends on the oxalate concentration and pH level [CITATION_2] . [CITATION_3] stated that the initial decay rate of 2,4-D was faster when the reaction was initiated by ferrous oxalate than that by ferrioxalate in the presence of H 2 O 2 and UV light. Since the information regarding the removal of chlorinated herbicide by ferrous oxalate/H 2 O 2 system is very limited, this project investigates the kinetics of the transformation of herbicide 2,4-D with ferrous oxalate and H 2 O 2 in the presence of UV light at two different hydrogen peroxide concentrations and various initial pH levels. ",
